               =20
<p>I am writing a Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) in Python and facing problem=
s with input data lengths that are not powers of 2. I came across recommend=
ations to pad such inputs with zeros to reach the nearest power of 2, but I=
 found the results are much different compared to standard implementations =
(numpy)</p>
<p>Here's my implementation of the FFT:</p>
<pre class=3D"lang-py s-code-block"><div class=3D"mtn4 d-flex jc-end ps-sti=
cky l0 mrn4" data-nosnippet=3D""><button class=3D"py2 mb2 s-btn s-btn__mute=
d s-btn__xs fs-caption ff-sans d-flex ai-center js-copy-button fc-black-400=
 h:fc-black-500 f:bg-black-200" type=3D"button"><svg aria-hidden=3D"true" c=
lass=3D"svg-icon iconCopy mr4" width=3D"17" height=3D"18" viewBox=3D"0 0 17=
 18"><path d=3D"M5 6c0-1.09.91-2 2-2h4.5L15 7.5V15c0 1.09-.91 2-2 2H7c-1.09=
 0-2-.91-2-2zm6-1.25V8h3.25z"></path><path d=3D"M10 1a2 2 0 0 1 2 2H6a2 2 0=
 0 0-2 2v9a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V4a3 3 0 0 1 3-3z" opacity=3D".4"></path></svg>Copy=
</button></div><code data-highlighted=3D"yes" class=3D"hljs language-python=
"><span class=3D"hljs-keyword">def</span> <span class=3D"hljs-title functio=
n_">myfft</span>(<span class=3D"hljs-params">x</span>):
    N =3D <span class=3D"hljs-built_in">len</span>(x)
    <span class=3D"hljs-keyword">if</span> N &lt;=3D <span class=3D"hljs-nu=
mber">1</span>:
        <span class=3D"hljs-keyword">return</span> x
    evens =3D myfft(x[<span class=3D"hljs-number">0</span>::<span class=3D"=
hljs-number">2</span>])
    odds =3D myfft(x[<span class=3D"hljs-number">1</span>::<span class=3D"h=
ljs-number">2</span>])
    t =3D np.exp(-<span class=3D"hljs-number">2j</span> * np.pi * np.arange=
(N) / N)
    f =3D np.concatenate([evens + t[:N//<span class=3D"hljs-number">2</span=
>] * odds,
                        evens + t[N//<span class=3D"hljs-number">2</span>:]=
 * odds])
    <span class=3D"hljs-keyword">return</span> f
</code></pre>
<p>This gives the same result as numpy.fft.fft() when the input length is a=
 power of 2, but gives a different result for zero padding input.</p>
